        <ab>dr̥ṣṭa<unclear>M</unclear></ab>
        <!--
dr̥ṣṭaM is in line with l1 of the body, but in the margin on the left. The text of l1 begins with an indent, so there is a space of 1-2 characters between the two blocks.
-->
        <lb n="02"/>
        <ab>siddhaM</ab>
        <!--
siddhaM is also in the left margin, but clearly comprises a block separate from dr̥ṣṭam. It is near, but slightly above, line 3. Line 3 is not indented. In all likelihood both dr̥ṣṭam and siddham were inscribed after the body text, but while there was space left for dr̥ṣṭam at the top left, siddham was engraved in the left margin, which is quite spacious.
-->
        <p><pb n="1v"/><lb n="1"/>vatsagulmād dharmma-mahārājasyāgniṣṭomāptoryyāma-vājapeya-jyoti<lb break="no" n="2"/><unclear>ṣṭo</unclear>ma-br̥haspati-sava-sādyaskra-catur-aśvamedha-yājinas samrāja<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> <sic>vr̥</sic><lb break="no" n="3"/><sic>ṣṇ<unclear>i</unclear></sic><space type="binding-hole"/>vr̥ddha-sagotrasya <space/> hāritī-putrasya <space/> śrī-pravarasena-pautrasya
<lb n="4"/>dharmma-mahārājasya <space/> śrī-sarvvasena-putrasya <space/> dharmma-mahārājasya
<lb n="5"/>vākāṭakānā<unclear>M</unclear> śr<choice>
            <sic>i</sic>
            <corr>ī</corr>
          </choice>-vindhyaśakter vvacanāT<!--
The name vr̥ṣṇivr̥ddha in l2-3 must, as editors note, be a mistake for viṣṇuvr̥ddha which is consistent in other Vākāṭaka inscriptions and is also the form attested in standard gotra lists (#Mirashi_1963:93). The i of ṣṇi is not at all clear in the facsimile.
--><!--
In l5 Mirashi reads vākāṭakānāṁ followed by a superfluous punctuation mark. I see no anusvāra, and the mark is too low down in my opinion to be punctuation, so I believe it's a damaged halanta M. Sircar in SI agrees.
--></p>
        <p><!--
Do we want to mark up the language change, maybe with @lang added to p?
--><!--
Throughout the Prakrit bit, my spacing and compound analysis is uncertain and open to revision.
-->nāndīka<unclear>c</unclear>asa <subst>
