<lb n="18"/>revatije<space type="binding-hole"/>si<surplus>|</surplus> bhāgo <num value="1">1</num> caUttho tti <space/> Ācandādicca-kālako Apuv<unclear>v</unclear>a-da<lb break="no" n="19"/>ttīya datto|<!--
Mirashi reads the name at the end of l5 as nāndīkaḍa. Deshpande & Mahajan (DM) read nāndikaṭa. Sircar prints nāndīkaḍa, but talks about nāndīkaṭa in his footnote. I think ī is certain, and ḍ is unlikely; ṭ is not very likely either; I'd read it as c on account of its similarity to c in acārasiddhika in l22, though it looks more like v than c.
--><!--
At the beginning of l6, DM and Sircar read bhākā, Mirashi reads tākā. I think bh is a bit more likely, but e.g. the t of majjātā in l19 is very similar too.
--><!--
DM, Sircar and Mirashi agree on lakkhoppakābbhāse (except that Sircar has ppā instead of ppa, but this is probably a typo), so I retain the reading. The kh of kkho could be something else, but nothing Prakritish (e.g. ktro). The ā of kā is not visible in the facsimile. Bbhā does not look very convincing: the upper part looks like p (though the b of bala in l8 is not much different), and the lower part like d. Still, taken together, bbhā (or bbha) is probably the best guess. (Or could this be something corrected to dde, to give us °oddese? But o attached to the preceding k is even less likely than a.)
--><!--
Sircar prints ākāśa in l6, but this must be a typo.
--><!--
DM read paṭṭesu in l6; I believe Sircar's and Mirashi's paddesu is more likely.
--><!--
Mirashi prints ihābhuttike instead of ihāmuttike in l9; this is definitely a typo.
--><!--
The superfluous punctuation character in l10 (as well as all other editorially deleted punctuation characters unless otherwise noted) is a small vertical, bulging to the left like an opening bracket, below the baseline. Some of the others look more like a mirrored J or even an U. Also, though I delete these marks for standardisation, they are clearly not random but mark the items of a list.
--><!--
Mirashi prints an anusvāra after bhālandāyaṇa-sagottesi in l10. I do not see it, nor do DM or Sircar read it.
--><!--
I accept Mirashi's reading of jivujjesi in l10. DM read situjjesi, Sircar follows. The first character could be just about anything from the facsimile and it probably, but not certainly, has an i mātrā. The second character could be a number of things with u (tu looks more likely in fact than vu), but it could also be ka or A/Ā.
--><!--
Mirashi again reads an anusvāra after the first sagottesi in l11, noting that it "is very faint, but it is there". Sircar and DM do not read this. I see a definite dot to the _left_ of the i mātrā (practically above tte) which may or may not be what Mirashi saw as an anusvāra.
--><!--
Like Mirashi and Sircar, I mark up the ka of kosika in l16 as unclear. The intent is clearly ka, but the shape is strange; possibly tu was inscribed first, then corrected to ka by inverting the hook, but the character still has no right arm, perhaps not added because the following sa is very close.
--><!--
For deAjjesi in l12, DM and Sircar read desujjesi. I believe Mirashi must be right, deajjesi sounds more plausible. Compare the uncertain jivujjesi in l10, which in my opinion may also be X-Ajjesi.
--><!--
The punctuation mark after deAjjesi is actually below the si, not after it, though there is some space. The punctuation mark of the following sagottesi is likewise under the si.
--><!--
I think veṇhujjesi in l12 may in fact be viṇhujjesi. There is a dot above the apparent ve, which together with the apparent e mātrā may be remnants of an i mātrā. (Though cf. vaṇhu in l30, where there is definitely no i mātrā.)
--><!--
Mirashi emends paḍehi in l15 to paṭehi. DM actually read paṭehi.
--><!--
Only Mirashi reads the numeral 1 in l18. DM read nothing here, while Sircar reads a punctuation mark. Since all other punctuation marks so far have been quite different (this one is a short dash at midline-height), Mirashi must be right in seeing it as a numeral, which also makes very good sense.
--><!--
caUttho in l18 is our first instance of aü/aï diaeresis in the corpus. I just use the capital U to show that this is a full vowel, but perhaps ü should be used to reduce ambiguity?
--></p>
        <p>puvva-rāyāṇumate ya se cātuvvejja-ggāma-majjātā-parihāre vita<lb break="no" n="20"/>rāma<unclear>|</unclear> taṁ jathā <space/> A-raṭṭha-saṁvviṇayika<surplus>|</surplus> A-lavaṇa-keṇṇa-kkhataka<surplus>|</surplus> A-hiraṇṇa-dha<unclear>ṇṇa</unclear>-
