For saṁvviṇayika in l20, DM read saṁvvaineyika, while Sircar has saṁvviṇeyika. Neither seems correct from the facsimile; I follow Mirashi's reading.
--><!--
For keṇṇa in l20, Sircar reads (kle)ṇṇa, which seems unwarranted.
--><!--
The word kkhataka in l20 seems clear in the facsimile. DM and Mirashi read kkhanaka, while Sircar has khātaka (sic). While kkhanaka would be expected, the character in question is ta, not na. Sircar's omission of the initial k is probably a typo; I see nothing like an ā mātrā here. (Unless, perhaps, Sircar read the k, of which only the right arm is visible, as an ā mātrā? But then the rest of the letter doesn't really make a kh.)
--><!--
Mirashi notes that the i of ggahaṇi in l21 may have been deleted. It is certainly damaged.
--><!--
DM and Sircar read pārampara in l21; I follow Mirashi in reading parampara as there doesn't seem to be an ā mātrā.
--><!--
DM and Sircar read avāra in l22; I accept Mirashi's acāra which seems more likely next to the bit about acammaṅgālaka. The character does look more like v than c.
--><!--
I accept Mirashi's and Sircar's khaṭṭā in l22, though I see no ā mātrā (unless the next character is cā instead of co). DM read khaṭṭa.
--><!--
Mirashi prints acammaṅgālika in l22; the li is probably a typo.
--><!--
The punctuation sign after sopanidhi is a double vertical; otherwise it is like the others: small and below baseline.
--><!--
Sircar reads kutuppānta in l23; this may be a typo.
--><!--
The punctuation sign after mahākaraṇa in l24 is also below the last letter of the word.
--></p>
