<lb n="28"/>nigraha<supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied> <space type="binding-hole"/> karejjāmetti<!--
For śāsaṇa-vādam pamāṇaṁ in l25, DM read śāsana cādamyamāṇa. Mirashi expresses indebtedness for his reading to B. Ch. Chabra.
--><!--
For bu in l26, DM and Mirashi read (or at least print) vu, which seems unlikely. Sircar reads bu, noting that perhaps tu or vā was intended. For another thought, this may be a or ā corrected to vā. Perhaps the scribe began to engrave ābādhaṁ, then realised that he missed a letter?
--><!--
For the next word, DM, Mirashi and Sircar all read ābādhaṁ, with Sircar alone marking the ā as unclear. The character looks like sa (with the right limb atrophied): there is no hook whatsoever. There is, however, a little curve way below the character, atop the te of likhitehi in the next line, which may be the bottom of the hook of ā, so I accept the reading.
--><!--
As Mirashi notes, tissa in l27 is probably meant to be tassa.
--><!--
Mirashi in CII prints brāhmaṇehiṁ in l27. bāmha is clear, so his brāhma may be a typo. I see no anusvāra (of which he also prints one with likhitehi).
--><!--
For pari(ñña)pite in l27, DM read parikūpite. Sircar has pariñapita, while Mirashi gives parikupite, emending to "parikupitehi veditassa" which is imaginative but a bit wild. I am quite certain the solution is pariññapite.
--></p>
        <p><!--
Sircar reads the number in l29 as 5. Mirashi's and DM's 4 seems more likely, though the symbol is not identical to the one used for foliation.
--><!--
In l29 DM read samupāṇatthi. Sircar reads samuhāṇṇatthi, to mean sva-mukhājñapta, noting that the reading is not beyond doubt. There is definitely no double ṇṇ, only a single ṇ; Sircar's ṇṇ may be a typo. Mirashi reads samupāsatthi and translates "given by Us personally"; I am not sure how he arrives at that (unless he translates Sircar's reading instead of his own). Mirashi is the only one to note that we have correction here; he believes that the last three akṣaras of his samupāsatthi "are incised over others which have been cancelled." I see no recognisable trace of correction in tthi, while after it there is a pretty clear śā that none of the previous editors note. I am far from sure, but I prefer Sircar's version. I don't know if tthi is plausible; I'd expect tti. In fact, now that I think about it, the character may be tthi corrected to tti. Also, perhaps it is not sva-mukhājñapta but sa-mukhājñapti, a CP accompanied by oral orders?
--><!--
The pa of seṇāpatiṇā in l29 may be a correction from va or sa. DM and Sircar read seṇa; I believe Mirashi is right in readin ṇā.
--><!--
The punctuation symbols transcribed as double daṇḍas in l30 are long double verticals, like modern double daṇḍas.
--><!--
The ornamental glyph in l30 is a four-petalled flower. The closer is a horizontal dash.
-->sāvvaccharaṁ <num value="37"><g type="numeral">30</g> 7</num> hemanta-pakkhaṁ paḍhamaṁ
